{
  "text": "The uncertainty of cereal prices, the availability of feedstuffs and consumer preferences have increased the interest of farmers for forage-based systems in these areas. Low-input, self-sufficient pasture-based systems can satisfy societal demands such as landscape and biodiversity conservation or ethical concerns about food production and are less vulnerable to market changes [CITATION_1] . Forage-based systems in cattle production have longer duration than concentrate-based fattening systems, thus, they require the prepubertal castration of the animals to reduce their sexual and aggressive behaviour.",
